  "opinion": "As a retired man who grew up in Los Angeles with limited formal education but a deep appreciation for creativity and the natural world, I've watched how stereotypes can quietly shape people's lives. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't about innate ability but about the psychological burden of being labeled as 'not belonging' in fields where you're often the minority. When a young girl sees girls in her class struggling with math because they're told 'boys are better at math,' that's stereotype threat in action. It's not a problem of intelligence but of belief. I remember my own childhood when teachers would say things like 'you're not a math person,' which made me doubt myself even though I loved solving puzzles. We should address this by creating environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. In my community, we've seen this happen with our local youth soccer teams—when kids were told they weren't 'good at sports,' they stopped trying. So, how do we fix it? Simple: stop labeling and start encouraging. Schools should focus on curiosity, not test scores. Let kids know that failing is part of learning, not a sign of weakness. I've traveled a lot, and I've seen how different cultures handle this—some places have programs that pair students with mentors who share their backgrounds. That works because it builds trust. In Hinduism, we believe in the importance of self-doubt as a path to growth, so this aligns with our values. We need to shift from 'you can't' to 'you can try.' It's not about changing people—it's about changing how we see them. And that, my friends, is the most important thing.",
